\title{Synchronization: trit-tick GF(3)}
\taxon{protocol}
\author{monaduck1069}
\date{2026-03-29}
\tag{synchronization}
\tag{gf3}
\tag{trit-tick}

\p{Each modality receives a trit assignment in #{GF(3) = \{0, 1, 2\}}. Temporal alignment via arithmetic in the three-element Galois field.}

\subtree{\title{The trit-tick Protocol}
\ul{
  \li{Each device stamps events with its GF(3) phase}
  \li{Synchronization is verified by checking that trit sums across modalities satisfy the constraint equations}
  \li{\strong{Composable}: adding or removing a modality means adding or removing one trit assignment. No global reconfiguration}
  \li{\strong{Mix-and-match}: any subset of the stack can synchronize without the full stack being present}
}
\p{This replaces traditional master-clock architectures with a distributed, algebraic synchronization scheme. The math is trivial (addition mod 3). The consequence is profound: the stack is not a fixed system but a composable kit.}}
